post_text:
We are excited to announce SEED SESSIONS, a new student group that will be led by H. Adam Harris. This affinity space for BIPOC students will be a resource for students of color at SPCPA.

H. Adam's goals for the group include:
1. Working to maintain anti-racist practices at the school.
2. Providing space for reflection and conversation.
3. Celebrating each other and finding our collective joy.

The name of the group is based on the quote shared by BIPOC folk around the world: "They tried to bury us. They didn't know we were seeds". The artwork is by local artist, Ricardo Levin Morales.

CURRENT STUDENTS: check your emails for participation information!

First day of physics class, and it’s already time for an experiment!
The challenge? Roll a ball down a ramp, across a flat surface, and off the edge of a table. The ball must consistently land and stay in a small paper cup.

Try it yourself! It's much harder than it looks.

J-Term 2021
EVERY 28 HOURS

Directed by H. Adam Harris

Originally developed through the Oregon Shakespeare Festival, The Every 28 Hours project consists of over 70 short plays that reflect the current civil rights movement, and tools to help the community address these issues, grow empathy, and become healthier.

Rehearses and Performs at Mixed Blood Theatre Company

To all SPCPA seniors, the Sites Family is proud of you; continue to be, give and receive love!

SPCPA is accepting applications for a part-time Visual Arts teacher (.25-.50 FTE). The Visual Arts program is new and scheduled to open fall 2020 (first day of school, August 20).

SPCPA is a unique school where all arts instructors are working professional artists, teaching part time.
Note: Applicants must be an exhibiting artist who maintains an active creative practice, and whose professional resume reflects an exhibition history.

Please complete the application at the link below
and include:
Letter of interest
Professional resume
Teaching resume (if applicable)

https://www.applitrack.com/spcpa/onlineapp/JobPostings/view.asp?FromAdmin=true&AppliTrackJobId=243

To kick off our final week of school, Andrew Simonet, author, choreographer and activist, addressed SPCPA's class of 2020 Tuesday evening. It was a great opportunity to listen live to some words of encouragement and wisdom.
For anyone interested in reading some of Andrew's words, his open letter to artists, "Why Artists are Needed Now" can be read at this link:
https://madmimi.com/s/708e601

Thank you Andrew for taking the time to speak to our students as they head off into the next chapter of their lives!

post_text:
Celebrating the Class of 2020!
Thanks to a generous donation from the family of a SPCPA senior, all seniors had the opportunity to order a Senior Class T-Shirt, designed by our very own Dean of Students, Kyle Clemins!

In the face of this very strange ending to SPCPA’s Class of 2020’s high school career, the Lorsung/Boone Family Foundation graciously volunteered to cover the cost of the senior class t-shirts in recognition of their daughter and your fellow classmate, Sophie Lorsung. They wish every graduating senior the very best in their life pursuits…stay curious, challenge yourself, and find your happy.

We can't wait to see what you all do with your "Unlocked Potential!"
text:
Celebrating the Class of 2020!
Thanks to a generous donation from the family of a SPCPA senior, all seniors had the opportunity to order a Senior Class T-Shirt, designed by our very own Dean of Students, Kyle Clemins!

In the face of this very strange ending to SPCPA’s Class of 2020’s high school career, the Lorsung/Boone Family Foundation graciously volunteered to cover the cost of the senior class t-shirts in recognition of their daughter and your fellow classmate, Sophie Lorsung. They wish every graduating senior the very best in their life pursuits…stay curious, challenge yourself, and find your happy.

We can't wait to see what you all do with your "Unlocked Potential!"

Faculty About Town!

Through his work at the MacPhail Center for Music, SPCPA Musical Theatre teacher Joey Clark regularly partners with, and teachers music at senior homes around the Twin Cities.

With his face-to-face teaching put on hold for the time being, Joey has been engaging with his community through song in what he's calling "Quarantine Singalongs."

Check out his set from this afternoon with residents at the Episcopal Homes of Minnesota! He also made a stop yesterday at The Kenwood.

https://www.facebook.com/Episcopalhomes/videos/231860127903595/

Our next Scientist of the Week is in fact TWO scientists!

Ms.Peterson describes Lilliana Rice and Athan Fischer as, “a dynamic duo that have each other's backs and exemplify teamwork. They help each other out, study together, and seek out help when necessary. They motivate each other to do their best and continue to work through problems and learn from their struggles...true scientists.”

Stay tuned for more Scientists of the Week throughout our Distance Learning Period!

post_text:
Our first Scientist of the Week during Distance Learning is Brayli Carmichael!

Ms.Meleck chose her because, “Brayli worked really hard at the end of our in person classes and has continued to turn in high quality work before online learning even started. I am very proud of the effort she has put into Biology.”
•
•
•
Scientist of the Week was a new tradition at SPCPA. Science teachers took turns weekly to honor one of their students with the title “scientist of the week”. Students would have their picture posted to the Science Pod bulletin board, along with a comment from their teacher explaining why they were chosen. We will continue the Scientist of the Week throughout distance learning via social media instead!

post_text:
Alright SPCPA community, we’re playing a little game this week called, “Which J-Term am I”

Each morning a close-up picture will be posted from one of the J-Term 2020 show albums on Facebook. This might be a close up of a costume piece, a character’s hair, a set piece, prop or even a musical instrument. It could be anything.

Your job is to figure out from which show the picture was taken. Maybe you’ve seen the pictures so many times you’ve got them memorized, maybe you’re the one wearing the costume, or maybe you go check out the photo albums on Facebook and do some sleuthing.

Whatever your strategy, the first person to correctly guess the show in the comments on Instagram OR Facebook will get a shout out when the full picture and answer are revealed each afternoon.

READY TO PLAY? Here is your first close-up:

post_text:
Advanced English 10 students recently finished a research project on current social issues.
After becoming informed on a topic important to them, students created a piece of art that included commentary about their issue.
Topics included hostile architecture, environmental problems, cost of college and LGBTQ representation, among others.
Projects came in the shape of poetry, performance, visual arts and even a cake.

Advanced English 10 students recently finished a research project on current social issues.
After becoming informed on a topic important to them, students created a piece of art that included commentary about their issue.
Topics included hostile architecture, environmental problems, cost of college and LGBTQ representation, among others.
Projects came in the shape of poetry, performance, visual arts and even a cake.

post_text:
Today, the Governor announced that all public schools in Minnesota will close beginning Wednesday, March 18, to help slow the spread of COVID-19.

SPCPA has decided to cancel all classes beginning TOMORROW (Monday, March 16).

However, SPCPA will be open Monday (March 16) and Tuesday (March 17) for students who wish to meet with academic teachers. All academic teachers will be available between 8AM-4PM.

Students and families: please look for an email soon about how SPCPA will transition to remote academic learning. SPCPA will suspend learning in all arts classes until students return to campus.

SPCPA student Ella Martin as Gloria in WAIT UNTIL DARK at Lakeshore Players Theatre. Have a great opening weekend!

Debuting on Broadway in 1966, this classic American thriller tells the story of, "Susan Hendrix, a blind yet capable woman, [who] is imperiled by a trio of men in her own apartment. Lakeshore Players have an age recommendation of 16+ for this show. More information at https://www.lakeshoreplayers.org/wait-until-dark

#alumabouttown⠀
⠀
SPCPA alum, Steven Grant is coming back to town in DISNEY ON ICE: ‘ROAD TRIP ADVENTURES’! ⠀
(March 12-15, ticket link: https://www.targetcenter.com/events/detail/disney-on-ice-1)

16 years ago Steven started his figure skating journey at home club, Woodbury Figure Skating Club. Since then he has become a double gold medalist with USFS, has passed his bronze medal in Ice Dance and competed on a national level in both synchro and theatre on ice. ⠀
For the past 7 years he has been with the Disney On Ice company, traveling the world to over 36 countries. Steven has played roles such as Kristoff from 'FROZEN,' Young Simba from 'THE LION KING' and John Darling from 'PETER PAN.' ⠀
⠀
Steven plans to continue touring with Disney On Ice to share the love of skating and Disney with kids all around the world.

post_text:
Alum about the country!

Pianist Jason Flowers (SPCPA ‘14) will be performing on February 12th in New York City!
The performance is at 1 PM at the Marble Collegiate Church.

After graduating high school, Jason stayed in his home-state of Minnesota for while studying at the U of M. Flowers’ hard work paid off when he received the Frances Hall Ballard Scholarship at the Manhatten School if Music, taking him across the country to New York City. Studying there under Phillip Kawin, Flowers obtained a Bachelor of Music in Classical Piano Performance in 2019.
After numerous performances around NYC, Flowers was able to follow his mentor to the International Academy of Music in Italy and fulfill a dream of performing in that country.
Currently a Masters student at the Manhattan School is Music, Jason is expecting a Masters of Music in Piano Performance in 2021.

post_text:
Not your typical exam...

In the midst of finals season, a handful of SPCPA students came to school on a Saturday for a different kind of exam:
the Skills Proficiency Test from the Society of American Fight Directors (SAFD). We are happy to report that all participants passed!

This was all thanks to SPCPA teacher and founder of the @fakefightingcompany, Aaron Preusse. Aaron is the Mid America Regional Representative and a Certified Teacher with the SAFD. He also has a number of certifications in various combat styles, and has worked as both a stage actor, and Fight Director all over the Twin Cities.

Thank you also to Fight Master Geoffrey Alm who adjudicated the test.

post_text:
Do you know how to use a Clinometer? SPCPA students can teach you!

Students in Mindy Richmond’s Geometry class paired this angle and incline-measuring device with meter sticks and their knowledge of trigonometry to determine the railing height of one of the Lowry building’s many staircases.
This railing is far too tall to simply stack meter sticks on top of each other. Instead, students had to combine their efforts. They could then use their new tools and skills to calculate the railing’s height at different points of its incline.

post_text:
SPCPA Alum ELI NEWELL writes and directs new play, to premier at Chicago’s Raven Theatre!⠀

COLD TOWN / HOTLINE shares the story of five crisis hotline volunteers during the holiday season in Chicago, 1983. ⠀
Opening this weekend for its world premier! ⠀
https://www.raventheatre.com/stage/hotline/

After graduating from SPCPA, Eli Newell went on to get his B.A. from Northwestern University. Since then, he has had three world premier works: MASQUE MACABRE (co-creator/director), FAIR GAME (playwright/director) and now COLD TOWN / HOTLINE (playwright/director). These are in addition to a number of assistant directing credits around the Chicago area, and time spent as the assistant to Pulitzer Prize-winning playwright and screenwriter Doug Wright.

Passionate for Human Rights advocacy, Eli is also a facilitator for Unsilence, a social justice organization dedicated to illuminating hidden injustices through interactive storytelling.

Look out for his next project: an interactive TV series, placing viewers at the center of a snowy treasure hunt!

Congratulations Eli!

And the award goes to...SPCPA!

Last month, Principal Brian Goranson and Board Chair Michael Robins attended the Arts Schools Network Conference in Jacksonville, FL where they accepted the Arts Innovation Award on behalf of the school.

SPCPA was awarded this honor largely due to our J-Term program, which allows students the experience of a working artist as part of their studies. Students spend three weeks rehearsing, and ultimately performing, at local professional venues with local professional artists. SPCPA is proud to offer such experiences to their students, and is grateful for the recognition.

post_text:
If you could have dinner with anyone in history, who would you invite?
In Ms. Reinhart’s AP U.S History Class last week, students got to “dine” with social reformers from the mid-1800s.

Each student took on the role of a prominent figure from the movements of abolitionism, education, women’s rights, temperance, transcendentalism, or the medical field. As they “met” one another, students tried to find fellow reformers whose work best aligned with their own, while learning about the overall successes and challenges of social & political change during this era.

Who would you bring to dinner?

They work tirelessly, putting in long hours before and after school, to help make SPCPA a positive, and safe environment for our students.

Thank you Kyle and Dave for all you do for us, and for all you’ve done.

#alumabouttown

SPCPA Alum, Nicole King is back in Minneapolis as Shelby in the Guthrie Theater's production of STEEL MAGNOLIAS.

Since graduating from SPCPA in 2013, Nicole has traveled the country and the world perfecting her craft. She has a BFA in Acting from the Mason Gross School of Arts at Rutgers University, and has had the fortune of studying classical texts at Shakespeare’s Globe Conservatory in London, England. While there, she performed in a production of A MIDSUMMER NIGHT’S DREAM as Helena. (She later played Titania in a production at Rutgers).

Currently based in New York City, Nicole most recently spent time at the Syracuse Stage where she received a Syracuse Area Live Theatre (SALT) Award nomination for her title role in the world premier of POSSESSING HARRIET.

STEEL MAGNOLIAS is running now through December 15, 2019.

See the Guthrie Theater's website for ticket information
https://www.guthrietheater.org/shows-and-tickets/2019-2020-season/steel-magnolias/

But their son Will, about to have a child of his own, is determined to find the truth behind his father’s epic tales."

post_text:
Celebrating the #classof2020 with our wall of senior headshots!

Each year about half of our graduating seniors go off to arts auditions at colleges and universities around the country where they require a professional headshot alongside their resume. As a parting gift to these wonderful students, SPCPA coordinates sessions with a professional photographer at the beginning of their senior year. Each student gets only 3 minutes with Eli Edaji of Cadence & Eli, but their pictures always turn out great!

Good luck Seniors, we wish you the best as you prepare for your futures!

ALUM ABOUT TOWN
#alumabouttown
Zach Manske at MDT

At just 20 years old, SPCPA alum Zach Manske is choreographing a new piece for the Minnesota Dance Theatre's Fall Season.

His ballet-contemporary hybrid, CYCLICAL RAVE, is described by it's choreographer as exploring "routines within our daily lives and the importance of realizing the destructive comfort that can accompany this loop... it's really about stepping outside of boxes, not being afraid to take risks."

CYCLICAL RAVE will have it's world premier at The Lab Theater - Mpls on Friday October 11, 2019. The show runs weekends through October 18, 2019. Stay for a post-show discussion with Zach after the October 18th performance.

Read up on Zach's full bio and watch a clip from rehearsal in MDT's August feature of the up-and-coming choreographer:
http://mndance.org/real-life-billy-elliot-creates-new-work-for-mdt/

Tickets are on sale now at: https://www.showclix.com/event/fall-season

This past Saturday, Academic Program Coordinator Dustin Haug, and science teachers Marisa Meleck and Sara Peterson spent a glorious day in a workshop at Richardson Nature Center working with educators from across the state.
The workshop was presented by Climate Generation, an organization dedicated to empowering individuals and communities, especially youth and under-represented cultures, in order to combat and offset the effects of climate change. The major focus of this event was integrating the new Minnesota Science Standards with climate change science and indigenous/traditional ecological knowledge.
It was a fun day with lots of networking opportunities and hands-on activities. Everyone left refocused, inspired and "playfully activated!" All three teachers look forward to bringing what they learned at the workshop back to the SPCPA community.

Three SPCPA students received Commendations from the National Merit Scholarship Corporation (NMSC)!

CONGRATULATIONS!
Casey Johnson
Quinn Morrissey
Ella Nelson

Commended students are among the top 50,000 of more than 1.5 million students who entered the National Merit Scholarship Competition by taking the Preliminary SAT/National Merit Scholarship Qualifying Test (PSAT/NMSQT) in the fall of 2018.
This means our students are part of the top 3% in the country!
Although they performed exceptionally, they will not continue in the National Merit Scholarship Competition.

"Those being named Commended Students have demonstrated outstanding potential for academic success. These students represent a valuable national resource; recognizing their accomplishment...is vital to the advancement of educational excellence in our nation. We hope that this recognition will help broaden their educational opportunities and encourage them as they continue their pursuit of academic success." - spokesperson for the NMSC

Congratulations and thank you for the hard work you have put into your education!

SPCPA arts faculty, Elise Santa, is Music Directing BRIGHT STAR at @ [117475126208:274:Lyric Arts] in Anoka.

From their website:
"Inspired by a real event, BRIGHT STAR tells a sweeping tale of love and redemption set against the rich backdrop of the American South in the 1920s and '40s. When literary editor Alice Murphy meets a young soldier just home from World War II, he awakens her longing for the child she once lost. Haunted by their unique connection, Alice sets out on a journey to understand her past - and what she finds has the power to transform both their lives."

***Recommended for ages 12 and Up, contains mild reference to adult themes***

Get your tickets: http://www.lyricarts.org/bright-star
BRIGHT STAR runs now until September 29, 2019

Sponsor a Masterclass!

Master classes expand the arts curriculum by providing an opportunity for our students to learn from outstanding professional artists in our community.

$100 will bring a MASTER TEACHER into one of our classrooms for a FULL period.

Donors may specify the track, grade or class, or leave it up to the discretion of the arts faculty. Checks may be made out to SPCPA and dropped off in the main office at Lowry. All donations are tax-deductible.

Contact Arts Program Coordinator, Genevieve Bennett (bennettg@spcpa.org) with questions.

Thank you for your support of our students and the arts at SPCPA!

Do you find school drop off/pick up busy and crowded?
Are you getting blocked in by all the traffic?
Does drop off/pick up add extra stress to your day that you just don't need?

Try dropping off on St. Peter Street!

Construction on St. Peter Street is now finished, opening up new options for drop off/pick up. This entrance to the Lowry Building (305 St. Peter Street) is located right next to a designated Passenger Loading Zone which could lead to easier curbside access and calmer mornings/afternoons.

Students can enter the school with direct access to the Lab Theater, Instrumental area and Math classrooms.
This entrance will have staff supervision both before and after school.

post_text:
It's a #ThrowbackThursday at SPCPA!

We're jumping back to the first day of school with Ms. Reinhart's AP Comparative Government and Politics class.

For their first activity of the school year, AP COGO students made "Gummy Governments". To learn about the different types of governments students, used gummy bear treats to create scenes representing each one: democracies, theocracies, monarchies, dictatorships, oligarchies and communist systems.

AP Comparative Government and Politics is an elective Social Studies course for 11th and 12th graders that introduces them to the discipline of comparative political science. Throughout the year, students will study major political concepts, analyze patterns of political processes and behavior and their consequences, and compare and contrast political institutions across countries.

We all know that SPCPA rocks in the performing arts, but did you know that we're rocking the academic world too? The Minnesota Department of Education recently released some statistics from the 2018-19 MCA test data, and we have some exciting news to share!

Math MCA scores INCREASED 6% from the 2017-18 school year.

Reading MCA scores INCREASED 7.5% which puts us 20% above the Minnesota average.

Science MCA scores maintained their standing above the Minnesota average by 17%.

Congratulations and Thank Yous are in order to SPCPA students AND teachers for the wonderful work they do!

We are excited to welcome three new math teachers to our team this year. They have a combined 34 years of teaching experience, so SPCPA students are in great hands.

post_text:
Please take a moment to check out this public television feature about SPCPA alum Paige Quinlivan (Class of 2014). Paige was one of four "emerging artists" featured on the program (look for the images from two different J-Term projects).

Recently, her one-act play "John Hughes Wrote My Diary" was chosen for the Kennedy Center American College Theater Festival (KCACTF) one-act play contest. It was also a finalist (one of three!) for the KCACTF National Festival John Cauble Award for Outstanding Short Play and performed this week in Washington DC.

"I just believe in creating joy. And I think it's important as artists today not to just create art out of the sense of responsibility, but a sense of love for the world and altruism and looking at the art you create as a gift you can bestow to the people like you in the crowd who need to hear those stories and need that catharsis."

Beautifully said, Paige.
shared_text:
Postcards
April 19, 2019 at 12:20 AM ·

"I didn't think, 'Hey, I'm good at this.' I was like, 'Wow, I love this more than anything else I've done in my life.'"
Take a bow, Paige Quinlivan!

FACULTY ABOUT TOWN
Joey Clark

A shout out to SPCPA Musical Theatre Department Chair, Joey Clark, who was the Vocal Coach for the national anthem this past weekend at the Final Four at US Bank Stadium. He was selected by the NCAA and hired to coach and arrange the piece. The performers were four student athletes chosen from the four represented colleges of the Final Four teams. Joey found out who his performers were and what their musical ability and instruments were on Monday last week, they met for the first time on Friday morning for their one and only private rehearsal where they sat down and created an arrangement to perform the next day for 80,000 people in the stadium and hundreds of thousands on television! Joey was connected to the NCAA via his relationship with MacPhail Center for Music, where many SPCPA students receive outside private instruction.

SPCPA Alum Eric Mayson (Class of 2007) is releasing a new solo album TODAY, March 8, at his Ōp-Nope Release Party at Icehouse MPLS. Ōp-Nope also features SPCPA Alum Ross Orenstein (Class of 2008) and recent J-Term director Theo Langason (These Shining Lives).

Major Congrats to SPCPA alum, Paige Quinlivan (Class of 2014). Her one act play, "John Hughes Wrote My Diary," is one of eight national finalists for the John Cauble Award for Outstanding Short Play at the Kennedy Center, American College Theatre National Festival, in WASHINGTON D.C.!

In April, Paige will be flown out to D.C., where a reading of the play will be performed by a company of professional actors. As an 11th grader at SPCPA, her play, "Night and Day," was a highlight of the J-Term project, New Play Festival at Penumbra Theatre. She is currently a senior at University of MN, Morris.

Here's a print interview with Paige about her play:
https://www.kcactf5.org/itja-blog/reviews-passion-play-interviews-think-pieces

Way to go! Have a great time in DC, Paige!

text:
STUDENTS ABOUT TOWN
Alexander Arce Cohoon

...or actually in this case, STUDENTS ABOUT THE COUNTRY. Current SPCPA 11th grade dance student, Alexander Arce Cohoon, is competing on NBC's World of Dance! Tune in Sundays, beginning March 3 at 7PM! Check out the article for more info, and also learn more about Larkin Dance Studio, where a number of SPCPA dance students over the years have spent their after-school time.

Way to go, Alex!

Get your tickets now to see SPCPA dance instructors, Lisa "MonaLisa" Berman, Joe Tran, and Kaleena Miller at the The Cowles Center for Dance & the Performing Arts next weekend (March 8,9,10)!

BRKFST Dance Company & Kaleena Miller Dance "partner for a performance that merges the dynamic art forms of breaking and tap dance. With rhythm and movement as their foundation, BRKFST Dance Company and Kaleena Miller Dance celebrate the roots and technique of their respective movement styles while pushing them to new heights in this electrifying collaboration."

Don't miss this exciting opportunity to see these SPCPA teachers practice what they teach!

post_text:
Congratulations to SPCPA 10th grader, Dominic Cudd, the winner of Zeitgeist's 24th annual Eric Stokes Song Contest!

"Named in memory of late composer Eric Stokes, the contest is designed to encourage and celebrate amateur composers throughout the Twin Cities. Dominic's winning entry, Composition in B minor, will be performed by Zeitgeist at their annual Playing it Close to Home concert Feb. 8-9 at Studio Z." Dominic also composed an original score for the SPCPA J-Term project, The Little Prince.

Support the work of these four current SPCPA students performing in a section of a larger work with TU Dance at the Ordway Center for the Performing Arts. Tomorrow night! Saturday, October 27, 2018, at 7:30 PM!

Artistic Directors Toni Pierce-Sands and Uri Sands open TU Dance’s 15th anniversary season with a new retrospective work reflecting on the company’s rich repertoire of thought-provoking works. The anniversary program also features the Ordway’s first commission for TU Dance — With Love (2011), inspired by the paintings of African American artist Ernie Barnes and set to the legendary music of Donny Hathaway.

Go to https://ordway.org/event/tu-dance/
for tickets and more information!

https://www.twincitiestap.com/new-events/2018/10/18/tctf18-showcase

It's exciting to see current students engage in work in the community with current instructors!

ALUM ABOUT TOWN #alumabouttown

RYAN COLBERT (SPCPA Class of 2010)

Be sure to check out the Guthrie Theater's production of FRANKENSTEIN--PLAYING WITH FIRE, before it closes on October 27. The title role is played by SPCPA alum, Ryan Colbert (pictured below)!

Ryan is receiving terrific notices for his work in the piece:

"It is Ryan Colbert as Victor that drove the play’s heartbeat. Even though Victor is molded to be emotionally awkward to the point where it is played for some face-palming laughs, Colbert breathes so much life into the play as he conveys a man ruled by a duty that no one else understands: to discover all that is out there."
--MN Monthly

"Colbert commands his scenes with youthful vitality and volatility as a young student on fire for exploring the brave underworld of biological experimentation."
--Lavender Magazine

Get your tickets here: https://www.guthrietheater.org/shows-and-tickets/2018-2019-season/frankenstein/

Congrats, Ryan-and have a great final couple of weeks!

STUDENTS ABOUT TOWN #studentsabouttown

ANANDA CORDOVA STUART

Be sure to see 12th grader, Ananda Cordova Stuart, at the Children's Theatre Company in the world premiere production of I COME FROM ARIZONA, directed by Lisa Portes. It opens tomorrow!

The play is about Gabi Castillo, a bright, 14-year-old Mexican-American girl living on the South Side of Chicago, who is accepted into a very different, elite high school. Through her Global Perspectives class, she learns secrets about her past and her parents, discovers her own inherited strength, and begins to understand what it means to take risks. In today’s world of immigration raids and Dreamers, fear and uncertainty, Gabi inspires a modern-day lesson in bravery, courage, and finding power in what seems like a powerless situation.

Ananda plays a number of roles, and also understudies the role of Gabi.

Get your tickets here (the show closes Nov. 25):

https://my.childrenstheatre.org/single/PSDetail.aspx?psn=7616

Have a fantastic run, Ananda!
